<% content_for :title, "Walkthrough — prepare a run" %>

<section class="walkthrough">
  <%= render "progress" %>

  <h1>You prepared this run. Notice there is no “Approve”.</h1>

  <p>
    Here is a pay run the preparer raised. If you are acting as the preparer, the
    real <b>Approve</b> control is simply absent — the very same button the
    resolver hides — because you cannot approve your own work.
  </p>

  <%= render @pay_run %>

  <div class="countersign">
    <span class="glyph">✕✕</span>
    <span>
      <b>Four-eyes rule:</b> whoever prepared this run can never be the one to
      stamp it. Sign-off needs a second signatory.
    </span>
  </div>

  <p>
    But what if you send the approve request anyway — the one the missing button
    would have sent? Try it. This posts to the <em>real</em> approve endpoint;
    the gate, not this page, does the refusing.
  </p>

  <p class="wt-actions">
    <%= button_to "Try to approve it anyway", approve_pay_run_path(@pay_run),
          class: "button--danger" %>
    <%= link_to "Next: hand it to an approver →", walkthrough_path(step: "approve"),
          class: "button" %>
  </p>
</section>
